result.execSummary:
The defendant Brian Avelino Torres was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Forgery-Uttering [Modifiers: Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: Defendant to pay restitution of $805.54 plus restitution surcharge of $80.55 for a total of $886.09.
Not ordered to pay DNA surcharge.

Obtain GED or HSED if not obtained in prison.

Obtain/maintain full time employment in an occupation acceptable to agent.   Not voluntarily quit employment without agent's approval.

Obey all rules and conditions established by the Department of Corrections.

No consumption or possession of alcoholic beverages.  No entering bars, taverns or liquor stores.

No consumption or possession of any controlled substances unless legally prescribed to defendant and take prescribed medication exactly as directed to be taken.

No possession of drug paraphernalia.

Not associate with known drug dealers, known drug users or their residences.

Not be present where controlled substances are used or illegally sold.

Obtain housing that is acceptable to agent.

AODA assessment and comply with any treatment and programming recommended.

Complete Department of Corrections' CGIP program.

Submit DNA sample if not previously submitted.

No contact with victims, except may write letter of apology and provide it to the victim witness coordinator.

Pay supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections.
